In Guy de Maupassant's short story, "The Necklace," the protagonist, Mathilde Loisel, is portrayed as a detestable character whose selfishness, ingratitude, and obsession with superficial appearance s that drives her to ruined life. Her nature is marked by a disregard for those who care for her, especially her husband, and an obsessive craving for luxury that makes her seemingly detestable. Mathilde’s inability to appreciate her modest but sufficient life reveals a profound sense of entitlement, disconnecting her from reality. This is evident in her desire for wealth and social status, believing herself to be above the life she has. For instance, she is described as suffering "from the poverty of her dwelling, from the wretched look of the walls, from the worn-out chairs, from the ugliness of the curtains and all those things, of which another woman of her would never even have been conscious, tortured her and made her angry." (12). Mathilde demonstrates a disregard for the life she has and a deep resentment that it fails to meet her unrealistic fantasies. This entitlement disconnects her from reality, making her feel constantly wronged by her circumstances rather than appreciating what she does have. The detestable behavior of Mathilde shines bright when Mathilde’s disdain is evident in her interactions with her husband, whose efforts to bring her joy are consistently dismissed.  As husband Monsieur Loisel goes to great lengths to bring Mathilde an invitation to the prestigious ball. Despite receiving the gift of the invitation and rather expressing gratitude towards her husband Mathilde is upset. “ she threw the invitation on the table with disdain” and complains she has nothing to wear. (14). Mathildes reaction scores her selfishness and ungratefulness, traits infuriate the readers.  Instead of focusing on her husband's efforts, she’s fixated on her appearances and the need for a new dress, despite the limited financial resources, her lack of concern for her husband’s sacrifices. She says “I have no dress, and therefore I can’t go to this ball. Give your card to some colleague whose wife is better equipped than I” (23).  This line reveals Mathildes ungratefulness, as she prioritizes superficial appearances over the genuine care
